Zephyr BLEManagerImpl::_Shutdown(): mark CHIPoBLE service mode disabled.

_Shutdown() calls bt_disable() but leaves mServiceMode == Enabled, so a
subsequent DriveBLEState() (whose advertise gate is mServiceMode == Enabled)
could re-enter StartAdvertising() -> bt_enable(). Set the service mode to
Disabled first, mirroring the ESP32/NimBLE BLEManagerImpl.

This matters when the application reclaims the BT-controller DRAM after
commissioning (see chip-patches/0005 + Malloc::AddReclaimedRegion): bringing
the controller back up would touch freed memory. It makes BLE strictly a
one-shot, commissioning-only resource per boot.

Upstream candidate: yes (aligns the Zephyr platform with the NimBLE one).

diff --git a/src/platform/Zephyr/BLEManagerImpl.cpp b/src/platform/Zephyr/BLEManagerImpl.cpp
index c5a4b5f582..d5de9a076c 100644
--- a/src/platform/Zephyr/BLEManagerImpl.cpp
+++ b/src/platform/Zephyr/BLEManagerImpl.cpp
@@ -264,6 +264,11 @@ CHIP_ERROR BLEManagerImpl::_Init()
 
 void BLEManagerImpl::_Shutdown()
 {
+    // Mark CHIPoBLE disabled before tearing the controller down so a later
+    // DriveBLEState() cannot re-enter StartAdvertising() -> bt_enable(). On
+    // platforms that reclaim the BT-controller DRAM after commissioning, bringing
+    // the controller back would touch freed memory; keep BLE one-way per boot.
+    mServiceMode = ConnectivityManager::kCHIPoBLEServiceMode_Disabled;
     bt_disable();
 }
 
